n: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">In t=
his week&#8217;s edition of &#8220;Get Fucked, Cancer&#8221;, scientists us=
ed mRNA technology to temporarily shield healthy cells from radiation damag=
e during cancer treatment without protecting tumors. </p><p style=3D"margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span=
>To do so, they copied a trick from tardigrade. Tardigrades</span><strong> =
</strong><span>are a tiny, water-dwelling micro-animal known for its extrem=
e survival abilities, including resisting radiation and extreme temperature=
s. They make a special protein (Dsup) that shields their DNA, so researcher=
s used mRNA to temporarily make human cells produce this same protein. They=
 packed the mRNA into tiny fat bubbles and delivered it to areas that often=
 get damaged during radiation therapy, like the mouth and rectum. In mice, =
this protected healthy cells from radiation without helping tumors, meaning=
 cancer treatment still worked.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;co=
lor: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Add this to the grow=
ing list of reasons of why we think cancer is going to be cured in the next=
 decade. </p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px;line-height: 26px;"><hr style=3D=
